\fIwxIMAGE_OPTION_MAX_WIDTH\fR and \fIwxIMAGE_OPTION_MAX_HEIGHT:\fR If either of these options is specified, the loaded image will be scaled down (preserving its aspect ratio) so that its width is less than the max width given if it is not 0 \fIand\fR its height is less than the max height given if it is not 0. This is typically used for loading thumbnails and the advantage of using these options compared to calling \fIrescale/4\fR after loading is that some handlers (only JPEG one right now) support rescaling the image during loading which is vastly more efficient than loading the entire huge image and rescaling it later (if these options are not supported by the handler, this is still what happens however). These options must be set before calling \fIloadFile/4\fR to have any effect.

.RE


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
\fIwxIMAGE_OPTION_ORIGINAL_WIDTH\fR and \fIwxIMAGE_OPTION_ORIGINAL_HEIGHT:\fR These options will return the original size of the image if either \fIwxIMAGE_OPTION_MAX_WIDTH\fR or \fIwxIMAGE_OPTION_MAX_HEIGHT\fR is specified.

.RE

.PP
Since: 2.9.3


.sp
